 @cptnoremac  upscaling is basically built into modern game development now. It’s rare to see new games that don’t rely on it in some way. Do you really think MachineGames would’ve pushed ray tracing always on in Indiana Jones if DLSS—or any other upscaling—didn’t exist to make it feasible? Or that we’d see Nanite’s geometry without those specific optimizations?

On the Stable Diffusion side, it heavily depends on specialized GPU hardware like Tensor Cores and Cuda Cores, not just brute-force power. Without those specialized units, AI performance would tank. As for older games, most modern hardware can handle them with ease, and if there’s a slowdown, it’s usually the game engine that’s the issue—not raw GPU power.

I’m not saying raw performance doesn’t matter—of course it does, especially when a game or application doesn’t support upscaling. But as we keep pushing for bigger, faster GPUs, the performance gains aren’t as huge as they used to be. That’s why developers now lean heavily on AI and software optimizations instead of just throwing more teraflops at the problem. Physical and power constraints also limit how much you can scale up hardware, which is where DLSS, FSR, XeSS, and AI-focused cores come in to drive the next wave of performance in gaming and other GPU-heavy tasks.

